<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-060-016 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 243 971</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Sept 15 1991 v140 pY11(N) pA7(L) 14 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pocket-telephone system is planned: a wireless network with aglobal reach. (Inmarsat, the satellite consortium)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Edmund L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The International Maritime Satellite Organization (Inmarsat)details a plan concerning the possibility of developing aninternational mobile communications system that would use 30 or 40satellites.andP;  Inmarsat, which is a London-based satellite consortiaof 64 nations, is calling its plan Project 21.andP;  Motorola Inc hasproposed a similar plan involving 77 satellites.andP;  Some industryobservers note that the difficulty in developing a worldwidemobile communications system is the lack of available frequencies;Inmarsat is expected to address this issue at the WorldAdministrative Radio Conference in Feb 1992.andP;  Inmarsat isestimating the cost of putting the system in place at $500 millionto $1 billion.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsConsortiaInternational CommunicationsInternational Maritime Satellite OrganizationMobile Phones.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>